@WhereonEarth4K Political change is not fragmented and exclusionary in China. History inherently progresses in a spiral, not linearly. Modern governance philosophies are inseparable from several schools of thought dating back thousands of years. These schools, through millennia of ruling practice, have continuously experimented, corrected themselves, summarised their experiences, recorded them, and passed them on to future generations.

Of course, it also absorbed Marxism, adapting it into a Chinese version. Marxism doesn't provide specific operational instructions, it only provides direction. In the actual bureaucratic system, China still uses something derived from its own millennia-old elite system. The elite's selective system was/is used by the Yuan, the Qing, and the PRC.

China accepts the coexistence of two different political systems, ‘one country, two systems’, because the concept of the nation-state takes precedence over political systems. Chinese politics is a continuous and evolving process. Every dynasty and every ruler leaves behind their contributions to the system, which are understood, absorbed, and selectively used by contemporary China.
